You are building the AT&T Lead Request Tracking app.

Stack: Next.js 14 (App Router), TypeScript, Supabase, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, Vercel.

Rules:
- Always use TypeScript with strict types — no 'any'
- Use the App Router and server components by default; use 'use client' only when necessary
- All database access goes through Supabase server client (never expose service role key to client)
- RLS is enforced at the database level — always respect it, never bypass with service role on the frontend
- Two roles only: territory_team and owner — check role from users table, not just auth metadata
- Use React Query for all client-side data fetching
- Use shadcn/ui components for all UI elements
- Write Supabase queries using the JS client (not raw SQL in app code)
- All status transitions must write an audit_log entry — do this server-side
- Never hard delete users — set is_active = false
- sla_due_at is calculated on status change to 'submitted_to_client', not on record creation
- Keep components small and focused — split into /components, /lib, /types folders
- .env.local for all secrets — never hardcode credentials